Anton (Anjo) Peez

Hi!

I am a PhD Candidate at the University of Frankfurt, working out of Peace Research Institute Frankfurt (PRIF)s Berlin office, where I am currently the interim head.

I will be a Junior Visiting Scholar at Nuffield College, Oxford from 1012/2022 and was a Visiting Researcher at the Global Governance Research Unit at WZB Berlin Social Science Center from 12/202103/2022.

Research interests

My primary research interest is economic sanctions and their domestic consequences in the targeted country. I examine the effect of sanctions imposition on human rights and democracy, as well as how the regime type and state capacity of the targeted government shape the effects of sanctions. I am also interested in the drivers of public support for sanctions and under which conditions the general public and decisionmakers are more or less likely to support using them. This and other work examines norms in international politics.

A second broad interest of mine is empirical social science research design. My dissertation is largely quantitative and uses matching techniques for causal inference using panel data. I also use survey experiments and unexpected events data. I am interested in tools for knowledge aggregation and cumulation in the social sciences, including replication, extension, and systematic reviews. I have also published detailed archival work with embargoed records, as well as comparative case studies.

Formal education

  • Ph.D.in Political Science, University of Frankfurt, 20182022 (expected)

  • M.A.in Social Science Data Analysis, University of Essex, 20212023 (expected)

  • MPhil in International Relations, University of Oxford, 20162018

  • B.A. in Political Science (minor: Constitutional Law), University of Frankfurt, 20122015

Some recent publications

Peez, Anton (2022): Contributions and Blind Spots of Constructivist Norms Research in International Relations, 19802018: A Systematic Evidence and Gap Analysis. In: International Studies Review 24: 1, 132. DOI: 10.1093/isr/viab055.

Peez, Anton & Zimmermann, Lisbeth (2022): Contestation and norm change in whale and elephant conservation: Non-use or sustainable use?. In: Cooperation and Conflict 57: 2, 226245. DOI: 10.1177/00108367211047138.

Brockmeier, Sarah & Peez, Anton (2021): Akteneinsichten: Die deutsche Auenpolitik und der Vlkermord in Ruanda. [German Foreign Policy and the Rwandan Genocide] Berlin: Heinrich Bll Foundation. SocArXiv DOI: 10.31235/osf.io/wd27k. [in German the first study on the subject with access to embargoed Federal Foreign Office records.]

A full publication record is available at my institutional website.

Recent policy writing

Co-author and co-coordinator, Peace Report/Friedensgutachten 2022 chapter on economic sanctions.

Abb, Pascal/Attia, Hana/Brzoska, Michael/Daase, Christopher/Deitelhoff, Nicole/Grauvogel, Julia/Peez, Anton (2022): Only a Means to an End: The Conditions for Sanctions Success. In: Friedensgutachten 2022. Chapter 4, 110131. Bielefeld, Germany: Transcript. [in German the annual joint yearbook of Germans largest peace and conflict studies institutes.]

Selected media from the Peace Report/Friedensgutachten on sanctions issues in particular: Tagesschau, Die Zeit/DPA, FAZ, and elsewhere.

Teaching

I taught advanced undergraduate/graduate courses on sanctions and on social science research design in the 2022 summer semester at the University of Frankfurt (0407/2022).

Other interests, projects, and media

Outside of work, I enjoy road and trail running, collage, and watching baseball.

I occasionally offer scholarly opinions based on my research, including in ZDF heute, HR2 Kultur (1, 2), HR Info, Frankfurter Neue Presse, and elsewhere.

A while back, I researched, visualized, and published data-driven journalism at Einfacher Dienst, mostly focusing on German domestic politics. Our results and work were featured in FAZ, taz, Deutschlandfunk Nova, the ZDF Heute-Show, and VICE Germany, among other outlets.

In the past, I have worked for or interned at the German Bundestag, Goethe-Institut Kigali (Rwanda), the Federal Statistical Office, and the Federal Institute for Population Research.
